Introduction

Introduction¶

110,527 medical appointments with 12 associated variables (characteristics) are included here to analyze the relationship between different variables and the show up of patients at their scheduled appointment day. The most important one if the patient show-up or no-show to the appointment. The column names are: PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age Neighbourhood, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received, No-show.

Note: we will interpret the 1s and 0s in the dataframe in the following manner: 1 as True and 0 as False

1.1.2 Questions for analysis:¶

  1. Is there a relationship between scholarship and No shows?
  2. Is there a relationship between hipertension and No shows?
  3. Is there a relationship between Neighbourhood and No shows ?
  4. Is there a relationship between diabetes and No shows?
  5. Is there a relationship between Alcoholism and No shows?
  6. Is there a relationship between Handicap and No shows?
  7. Is there a relationship between SMS_received and No shows?
  8. Is there a relationship between age and No shows?
  9. sorting the factors that affect the show up of patients in a decsending order.

From the above observation of unique values, we saw that the Handicap column has 5 unique values (0,1,2,3,4) , while the website of kaggle said that the Handicap column has only two values, which are True and False (1,0) , therefore we will consider here that the Handicap column values (2,3,4) are error values and we are going to replace these values with 1

In [15]:

1.1.3 Is there a relationship between scholarship and No shows?¶

Name: No_show, dtype: int64
In [49]:
df.groupby("Scholarship")["No_show"].value_counts().plot(kind='bar'  , figsize=(4,4))
plt.title("Counts of patients (with/without) scholarship who (show up/No show)")
plt.xlabel("Scholarship, No_Show")
plt.ylabel("Counts")
Out[49]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Counts')

It is seen from the above figure that the number of patients with scholarships who show up their appointment (1, No) is less than the number of patients without scholarships who don't show up their appointment (0, yes), therefore scholarship has a minor effect on show up.

Now, we want to calculate the probability that a patient without a scholarship will No show

In [48]:
scholarship_probability =   19025 /(19025 + 73106 )
print(scholarship_probability)

0.2064994410133397

Result:

Therefore, a patient without scholarship is probable to show up his scheduled appointment by (0.79/0.21) = 3.8 more times than a patient who did not show up

Conclusion¶

The main objective of this Dataset investigation was to find what probable factors may influence the show up of patients at their scheduled appointment. For this intent, eight factors were analysed in this study to find their associated probabilities in the show up of patients at their scheduled appointment. The results of this study can be summarized in the following Bar plot of the probabilities of different factors influencing the show up of patients at theit appointment.

In [46]:
probabilities.plot(kind = "bar" , figsize= (8,5))
plt.title("Probability Distribution of different factors affecting patients No show")
plt.xlabel("Factors")
plt.ylabel("probability of No show")
Out[46]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'probability of No show')

It is seen from the above figure that Alcoholism is associated with the highest probability that a ptient will No show, followed by scholarship, then comes( Hipertension, Diabetes and Handicap) with equal probabilities, and the least probability is associated with the SMS_received factor.

with respect to "Neighbourhood" factor: It was found that there are two Neighbourhoods with the highest counts of No shows, these are:

JARDIM CAMBURI - 5243

MARIA ORTIZ - 3932

with respect to the age factor:

It was seen that the highest count of patients who did not show up lies in the age interval [20 , 30] , and their count decreases from 60 years upto 115 years.

Limitations¶

1- We have assumed that the values (2, 3, 4) given in column [Handicap] are errors, and we replaced it with the value 1. This may bias the calculated probability of patients with Handicap who No show towards higher values than reality.

2- The analysis made here is based on the calculation of probabilities, Probability is the mathematical calculation that evaluates the possibilities that exist for an event to happen when chance intervenes. Therefore, these calculations are just to predict and to compare what factors may render patients don't show up their appointment day. It does not tell us that any of the factors mentioned in this analysis is a real cause of a patient who don't show up.
